wcg_diff_general: There was probably more melancholy in my mind from reading a story that involves a tragic murder and the dissolution of a family unit as well. I think that may have been reflected at least in my early words, before the free association kicked in more in the later part.
wcg_strategy: I didn't really have any strategy as such, but probably names a lot of things that exist in my house since I kind of cast out my mind from my environment to things that were close by and then things associated with those items.
guess_experiment: To see whether priming you with a story with a given mood will make you more likely to type related words, or words that fit the tone or themes of the story you just read.
volition_explanation: I generally do not like sad stories like this, specifically because they tend to linger in my mind. I know that my mood is affected by the things I read, so if possible I prefer more upbeat stuff to prevent myself from being sad or angry. This made me feel somewhat sad, just because of the dissolution of the relationship, along with some fear as Claire was being followed and harassed.
wcg_diff_explanation: I think initially my thoughts were darker, so I had more downbeat and violent words to begin with. However, not long after I just kind of went on autopilot and just free associated with various words that came to mind spontaneously, which were more generic and unrelated to the story.
interference_explanation: I mostly wanted to keep reading it to try to figure out how it would connect with the first one, and I was surprised when it just abruptly ended with no apparent connection.
volition_interference_explanation: I've had a problem with a dimmer switch before, one that was not compatible with the LED lamp I bought, so I could relate to this. My elderly parents also have accidentally moved a dimmer slide and then wondered why the light was not so bright, so I have had similar experiences in the past. My thoughts about these connections may have started out unintentionally, but became intentional as I formed connections to my own experiences.
open_box: The only thing that kind of annoyed me was at the very beginning was when I was asked to count triangles, since it was not clear whether you meant only distinct individual shapes or also ones that could be formed by combining multiples into one (that is why I got it wrong the first time and right the second).
